    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>It indeed sets the stack size on a JVM.</p>\n\n<p>You should touch it in either of these two situations:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>StackOverflowError</strong> (the stack size is greater than the limit), increase the value</li>\n<li><strong>OutOfMemoryError: unable to create new native thread</strong> (too many threads, each thread has a large stack), decrease it.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The latter usually comes when your Xss is set too large - then you need to balance it (testing!)</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4116853,
      "reputation" : 11165,
      "user_id" : 3378204,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 91,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/jrjpD.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Eugene",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3378204/eugene"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 7,
    "last_activity_date" : 1659936956,
    "creation_date" : 1659936956,
    "answer_id" : 73273281,
    "question_id" : 4967885,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Add my two cents here, besides what mentioned, we can write a simple demo to show the effect of setting Xss.</p>\n<p>Generally speaking, it controls the stack size arranged to each thread.</p>\n<pre><code>    public static void main(String[] args) {\n        try{\n            recur();\n        }catch (StackOverflowError e){\n            System.out.println(depth);\n        }\n    }\n\n    static int depth = 1;\n\n    public static void recur(){\n        depth++;\n        recur();\n    }\n</code></pre>\n<p>After compiling above code, you will see the <code>depth</code> (the invoke hierachy) grows together with the passed <code>Xss</code> settings.</p>\n<p>The output of <code>java -Xss1m com.eugene.Main</code> is <code>21638</code> and the output of <code>java -Xss2m com.eugene.Main</code> is <code>48325</code> at my local machine.</p>\n"
  } ],
